==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*haubiþa-''.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[haved|hāved]], Old Saxon [[hoƀid|hōƀid]] (Dutch [[hoofd]]), Old High German [[houbit]] (German [[Haupt]]), Old Norse [[haufuð]], Gothic [[𐌷𐌰𐌿𐌱𐌹𐌸]].  The Germanic source was apparently related in some way to Latin [[caput]], Greek [[κεφαλη]], Sanskrit [[कपालम्]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'hæavod/

===Noun===
'''hēafod''' ''n'' (Plural: '''hēafdu''')

# the [[head]] of a person or animal
# the [[hair]] of the head
# a [[master]] or [[chief]]

